1 Background

A section of the South Fork Clearwater River near milepost (MP) 28 has been identified as a potential migration barrier for adult steelhead, particularly during periods of elevated flows. Elevated water velocities in this reach are hypothesized to impede or occasionally prevent upstream migration, limiting access to spawning habitat in the upper mainstem and its tributaries. Previous research suggests that when river discharge exceeds approximately 1,000 cfs in the reach, at least one hydraulic feature produces velocities that surpass the burst swimming capacity of a 90 cm steelhead (Timm et al., 2018, 2017). Earlier observations by Nez Perce Tribe (NPT) staff indicated that a velocity barrier may begin to form at flows above 600 cfs, based on readings from the former Elk City gage. Additionally, radio telemetry data collected from 2013 - 2017 (Cleary, 2019) showed that relatively few steelhead spawned upstream of river kilometer (rkm) 71, which corresponds to the location of the suspected high-velocity reach (Figure 1.1).

Figure 1.1: Estimated spawning locations for adult steelhead in the South Fork Clearwater River from a radio telemetry study conducted in 2013 - 2017.

This report presents a preliminary assessment of adult steelhead passage at a suspected velocity barrier on the South Fork Clearwater River using detections of PIT-tagged fish. Key detection sites include SC3 (downstream of the barrier) and SC4 (upstream). The analysis includes adults PIT-tagged at Lower Granite Dam and those tagged at various locations, including within the South Fork Clearwater River.

We focus on whether PIT-tagged adults detected at SC3 later appear at SC4, indicating successful upstream passage â€” or a lack thereof â€” across the high-velocity reach. We also examine how factors such as juvenile release location and river discharge relate to these â€œconversionâ€ rates. Although the primary focus is steelhead, adult spring/summer Chinook salmon PIT detections are included for comparison.

To support this evaluation, the number of PIT-tagged juvenile steelhead within Newsome Creek releases was increased starting in 2022 (Table 1.1). The first 1-ocean adults from these releases returned to spawn in spring 2024, with 2-ocean adults expected in 2025. Releases from 2023 will also begin returning as 1-ocean adults in spring 2025.

This preliminary evaluation is intended to evaluate adult conversion rates up-to-date since the SC3 and SC4 sites were installed in 2021 and to provide the baseline monitoring for responses to conversion rates if and when actions are taken to alleviate barriers in the study reach. This evaluation is preliminary and ongoing and will continue to be updated as additional years of data are collected and analyses are revised to address research and management questions.

1.1 Study area

The section of river considered to be a potential velocity barrier is located near rkm 71 of the South Fork Clearwater River (Figures 1.2 and 1.3). Figure 1.2 and Table 1.3 show each of the instream PIT tag detection sites (IPTDS) used in the evaluation to detect tagged adult steelhead and sp/sum Chinook salmon, including their rkm from the mouth of the South Fork Clearwater River.

2 Evaluation

2.1 Data

Our evaluation used information from PIT-tagged adult steelhead and sp/sum Chinook salmon detected at any IPTDS in the South Fork Clearwater River during their upstream migration to spawn. We queried DART to identify all PIT tags observed at Lower Granite Dam in returning adult steelhead and sp/sum Chinook salmon, during spawn years 2022 - 2024, using the queryObsDART() function in the R package PITcleanr, and filtered those observations to identify any adult later observed at any IPTDS in the South Fork Clearwater River (Table 1.3). Note that the adult detection rates on the Lower Granite Dam adult fish ladder are essentially 100%, and thus, any PIT-tagged adult returning to the South Fork Clearwater River is expected to not be â€œmissedâ€. We then used the PIT-tag lists of returning adults to the South Fork Clearwater and queried their complete tag histories in PTAGIS which includes their mark and release information and any subsequent observations. The complete tag histories were then â€œcompressedâ€ and â€œfilteredâ€ using the compress() and filterDetections() functions in PITcleanr, respectively. For steelhead, we removed any detections after May 31 during the spawn year and for sp/sum Chinook salmon after September 15 to avoid detections of any kelts (steelhead only), shed tags, etc. Additionally, biological (e.g., sex, length) data for adults tagged at Lower Granite Dam are available from the Lower Granite Dam trapping database (LGTrappingDB). Additional data used in the evaluation (e.g., discharge) are described below. All data and code used in this evaluation are available at a GitHub site here.

2.2 Conversion Rates

First, we estimated annual conversion rates from SC3 to SC4 for steelhead and sp/sum Chinook salmon 2.1). The conversion rate provides an estimate of the percentage of PIT-tagged adults passing SC3 that arrived at SC4. For example, in spawn year 2024, we estimated that 140 PIT-tagged steelhead passed SC3, of which 13 (9.3%) were estimated to pass SC4. Table 2.1 provides the estimated number of tags passing both SC3 and SC4 and estimated conversion rates with standard error. Here, both natural- and hatchery-origin adults, including all release locations, are lumped.

Table 2.1: Table 2.2: Estimated tags observed at SC3 and SC4 by species and spawn year including conversion rates.
Species Spawn Year Est Tags SC3 Est Tags SC4 Conversion (%) Conversion SE
Chinook 2022 138 130 94.2 2.0
Chinook 2023 108 99 91.7 2.8
Chinook 2024 100 86 86.0 3.7
Steelhead 2022 108 15 13.9 8.9
Steelhead 2023 77 12 15.6 10.5
Steelhead 2024 140 13 9.3 8.0
Steelhead 2025 333 24 7.2 5.3

Conversion rates from SC3 to SC4 were above 90% for sp/sum Chinook salmon; however, conversion rates for steelhead were all below 20% (Figure 2.1).

Figure 2.1: Conversion rates w/ 95% confidence intervals for sp/sum Chinook salmon and steelhead from SC3 to SC4 on the South Fork Clearwater River.

Estimates of conversion rates can be confounded for several reasons. For example, most sp/sum Chinook salmon in the South Fork Clearwater River originate from tributaries upstream of the high-velocity reach whereas many steelhead originate from juvenile releases downstream of the reach. As such, it is expected that sp/sum Chinook salmon will have higher conversion rates due to their proclivity to migrate to their upstream natal areas.

2.3 Release Location

Because overall conversion rates from SC3 to SC4 can be confounded depending on where juveniles were released relative to the barrier reach (and their resulting â€œimpetusâ€ to pass the barrier), we next considered conversion rates for adult steelhead and whether they were released as juveniles downstream or upstream of the barrier. For steelhead, all upstream releases are from Newsome Creek releases. Table (2.3) shows the release location for all adults observed at IPTDS sites in the South Fork Clearwater; adults of unknown release location are oftentimes adults newly tagged at Lower Granite Dam.

Due to lower sample sizes of adults observed at SC3 and SC4 within years, we lumped across spawn years and summarized conversion rates by juvenile release locations (Table 2.5; Figure 2.2). To date, 70 adults from Newsome Creek have been observed at IPTDS within the South Fork Clearwater River, of which 41 have been observed at SC3 and eight observed at SC4. Although sample sizes are low, conversion rates for Newsome Creek releases do appear somewhat higher than downstream and unknown releases; however, rates are still substantially lower than for sp/sum Chinook salmon.

2.4 Discharge

Timm et al. (2018) indicated that at discharges exceeding approximately 1,000 cfs within the reach of interest, at least one very high velocity barrier emerges which exceeds burst swimming velocities for a 90 cm steelhead. Moreover, NPT personnel previously hypothesized that a barrier emerged within the reach when discharges exceed approximately 600 cfs at the previous Elk City gage. Although discharges are not currently measured in the barrier reach, flow within the reach is estimated to be approximately two times flow at the Elk City gage; and thus, when flows in the barrier reach are 1,000 cfs, flow at the Elk City gage would be approximately 500 cfs (Timm et al., 2017). Therefore, we estimated conversion rates from SC3 to SC4 when estimated flows at the Elk City gage are above or below 500 cfs (Table 2.7, Figure 2.4).

Unfortunately, the Elk City gage is no longer in operation and so we first evaluated correlation between the operational Stites Gage and the Elk City gage based on historical data (Figure 2.3). We used historical daily mean discharge estimates starting in 2023, the first full year the Elk City gage was in operation, through October 17, 2021, the last day of its operation. The relationship was then used to estimate daily mean cfs at the Elk City gage for recent years.

Figure 2.3: Linear regression of discharge (cfs) at the previous Elk City (13337500) gage with discharge at the Stites (13338500) gage.

Conversion rates when estimated discharges at Elk City were above 500 cfs (~ 1,000 cfs in the barrier reach) were lower than when estimated discharge was below 500 cfs (Table 2.7, Figure 2.4). Because we donâ€™t actually know the cfs when the adult approached the barrier reach, we used the estimated cfs at the Elk City gage when each fish was most recently detected at an IPTDS site in the South Fork Clearwater River.

3 Logistic Regression

Finally, we evaluated the probability of an adult being detected at SC4 (given it arrived at SC3) depending on species, release location, and predicted flow (cfs) at the previous Elk City gage at the time of last detection. To do so, we fit a logistic regression model using species, release location, and estimated flow as covariates and probability of arriving at SC4 as the response variable. A fish that successfully arrived at SC4 was a â€œsuccessâ€ = 1 whereas a fish only seen at SC3 was â€œsuccessâ€ = 0. Figure 3.1 shows observed fish that arrived at SC4 (1) versus those only seen at SC3 (0) with the estimated flow at last detection (dots) as well as predicted probabilities of arriving at SC4 depending on species, release location, and flow.

Figure 3.1: Estimated probability of an adult arriving at SC4 given arrival at SC3 based on the estimated flow (cfs) at the previous Elk City gage, by species and release location.

Figure 3.1 does demonstrate a predicted downward trend in the probability of a fish converting to SC4 as flow increases, at least for steelhead; however, standard errors for upstream releases of steelhead are large due to small numbers of observations.

4 Discussion

Previous studies have indicated that a partial velocity barrier to adult steelhead passage may occur near rkm 71, at least at higher flows (Timm et al., 2018), and that the majority of steelhead in the South Fork Clearwater River likely spawn below there (Cleary, 2019). Based on PIT-tagged adult returns in recent years, it is difficult to discern whether the high-velocity reach hinders or prevents upstream passage for adult steelhead; however, conversion rates for steelhead are remarkably lower than those for sp/sum Chinook salmon. Conversion rates for adult steelhead from SC3 to SC4 is below 20% in all years, including for individuals from juvenile releases from Newsome Creek.

The number of PIT-tagged juvenile steelhead within Newsome Creek releases was increased starting in spring 2022 (Table 1.1); 1-ocean adults from spring 2022 releases began returning to the South Fork Clearwater River in spring 2024 and we did observe a 3-fold increase in adults returning from those releases as expected. Two-ocean adults will begin returning in spring 2025; increased sample sizes and observations in future years will increase our ability to evaluate conversion rates in future years. Regardless, we have established monitoring for if and when restoration actions take place to address potential passage issues due to high stream velocities.

Our evaluation used season-long estimates of detection efficiencies to expand observed tags into estimates of tags passing each IPTDS, which in turn was used to estimate conversion rates. We recognize that detection efficiencies of IPTDS can be influenced by factors including river depth or dishcarge; however, we used season-wide estimates largely due to lower sample sizes at more extreme flows. We will explore stratifying estimates of detection efficiency for future years if increased PIT-tag returns allows.
